    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Something I noticed when working on a new plugin. Not blocking for me at all.\r\n\r\nIf you have a floating window (like in my case some sort of fullscreen zen window)\r\nAnd then open another fullscreen floating window on top of that, so with a higher zindex **AND** with `winblend=30`\r\n\r\n### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\nThe top window will blend with regular window (editor, non-floating windows).\r\n\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nThe top window should blend using zindex, so in this case with the zen window.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I noticed this issue when working on [nvim-scrollview](https://github.com/dstein64/nvim-scrollview), a plugin that shows scrollbars. The scrollbars are floating windows, and blend with the text that they would otherwise be covering. I encountered the same issue described in this ticket when the scrollbars were over some other floating window with lower z-index.\r\n\r\nHere are steps that can be used to reproduce the issue. Zeros are added as text to the main window. Then a floating window is created that has ones. A floating window with `winblend` is created on top of that, and the text that is blended are zeros, from the bottom window, as opposed to ones from the other floating window.\r\n\r\n```vim\r\n\" Create a new tab with all 0s for the text\r\n:tabe\r\n:call appendbufline(bufnr(), 0, repeat('0', 99999))\r\n:normal! gg\r\n\r\n\" Create a floating window with all 1s for the text\r\n:let opts1 = {'relative': 'editor', 'width': 30, 'height': 20, 'col': 5, 'row': 5, 'zindex': 100}\r\n:let bufnr1 = nvim_create_buf(v:false, v:true)\r\n:call appendbufline(bufnr1, 0, repeat('1', 99999))\r\n:let win1 = nvim_open_win(bufnr1, 0, opts1)\r\n\r\n\" Create a transparent floating window above the prior floating window\r\n:let opts2 = {'relative': 'editor', 'width': 20, 'height': 10, 'col': 10, 'row': 10, 'zindex': 200}\r\n:let bufnr2 = nvim_create_buf(v:false, v:true)\r\n:let win2 = nvim_open_win(bufnr2, 0, opts2)\r\n:call nvim_win_set_option(win2, 'winblend', 10)\r\n```\r\n\r\nHere's a screenshot I took after running those steps.\r\n\r\n<img width=\"380\" alt=\"14624\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/541289/142782888-b17830ff-c3a2-4f40-a76c-5342b06848f2.png\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
